_ending_here = max(x, max_ending_here + x)\n                max_so_far = max(max_so_far, max_ending_here)\n            return max_so_far\n        \n        # Total sum of the array\n        total_sum = sum(nums)\n        \n        # Maximum subarray sum using Kadane's algorithm\n        max_kadane = kadane(nums)\n        \n        # Invert the array to find the minimum subarray sum\n        inverted_nums = [-x for x in nums]\n        min_kadane = kadane(inverted_nums)\n        \n        # Maximum subarray sum in the circular case\n        max_circular = total_sum + min_kadane\n        \n        # If all numbers are negative, max_kadane will be the answer\n        # Otherwise, we take the maximum of max_kadane and max_circular\n        return max(max_kadane, max_circular) if max_circular != 0 else max_kadane\n```\n\n### Explanation:\n- **Kadane's Algorithm**: This is used twice, once to find the maximum subarray sum and once to find the minimum subarray sum.\n- **Total Sum**: This is the sum of all elements in the array.\n- **Maximum Circular Subarray Sum**: This is calculated as `total_sum + min_kadane`. This is because the minimum subarray sum that we exclude from the total sum will leave us with the maximum circular subarray sum.\n- **Edge Case**: If all elements are negative, `max_circular` will be zero (since `min_kadane` will be the sum of all elements, and adding it to `total_sum` will result in zero). In such cases, we return `max_kadane`, which is the largest single element in the array.", "estimated_date": 1538870400000}